Russian RTS Stock-Index Futures Advance as Oil Surges on Unrest

-- B y   H a l i a   P a v l i v a
-- 
2011-03-04T22:38:21Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-04/russian-rts-stock-index-futures-advance-as-oil-surges-on-unrest.html
  Russia ’s RTS stock-index gained as
oil surged on concern political turmoil in the Middle East will
cut supplies.  Futures on the dollar-denominated index expiring in March
rose 0.2 percent to 200,410 at 3:50 p.m. in New York yesterday.
The Market Vectors Russia ETF, a U.S.-traded fund that holds
Russian shares, fell 0.1 percent. The Micex Index fell 0.4
percent to 1,764.96 by the 6:45 p.m. close in Moscow yesterday.
Russian markets are open today and closed March 7-8 for a
national holiday.  “The trend is up” for oil, said  Mark Mobius , executive
chairman of Templeton Asset Management’s Emerging Markets Group
in an interview with Lisa Murphy on Bloomberg Television’s
“Fast Forward” yesterday. “Of course, there will be lots of
volatility. But if you look at the long-term trend, it’s
definitely up.”  Contracts on OAO Gazprom, the natural-gas export monopoly,
rose 0.3 percent, while those for OAO Lukoil, Russia’s second-
largest oil producer, advanced 0.1 percent.  Crude oil increased to a 29-month high yesterday and has
surged about 18 percent since the Libyan uprising began two
weeks ago. Output in  Libya , which holds  Africa ’s largest oil
reserves, has dropped by as much as 1 million barrels a day
since the unrest began, the  International Energy Agency  said
March 2.  Crude Gains  Crude for April delivery gained 2.5 percent to $104.42 a
barrel on the Nymex, the highest settlement since Sept. 26, 2008.
Futures are up 30 percent from a year ago. Oil, along with
natural gas, accounts for a quarter of Russia’s economic output.  The Micex fell as much as 0.8 percent, reversing an earlier
advance of as much as 0.6 percent yesterday.  “The sentiment on Russia turned slightly cautious ahead of
the long holiday weekend,”  Luis Saenz , the London-based
director of international sales at brokerage Otkritie Securities
Ltd., said in an e-mailed message.  The MSCI Emerging Markets Index of 21 developing nations’
equities gained 1 percent yesterday. The index has slipped 1.1
percent this year, compared with a 5.3 percent gain in the MSCI
World gauge of developed countries. The Standard & Poor’s 500
Index has gained 5.1 percent in the period.  Russia’s dollar-denominated RTS Index fell 0.3 percent to
2,012.68 yesterday.  Novatek, Russia’s second-biggest natural gas producer,
dropped 3.1 percent. VTB and Sberbank, the country’s biggest
banks, fell at least 1 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
